  {
    "slide_type": "image",
    "story_number": "13 or 14",
    "body": "<p style=\"text-align: left !important;\">A truck from Waste Management dumps a load of recyclables – cardboard, plastics, paper, cans and shattered glass — on the tipping floor of the company’s Materials Recovery Facility at Neville Island.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left !important;\">Waste Management collects recyclables in many communities in the North Hills and South Hills.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left !important;\">According to the most recent South Hills contracts, Waste Management no longer collects glass and mixed plastics.</p>",
    "background": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.13.jpg",
    "background_mobile": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.14.jpg"
  },
  {
    "slide_type": "image",
    "story_number": "13 or 14",
    "background": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.13.jpg",
    "background_mobile": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.14.jpg",
    "background_opacity": "0, 0, 0, 0.05"
  },
  {
    "slide_type": "image",
    "story_number": 15,
    "body": "<p style=\"text-align: left !important;\">Plastic bags, including the blue recycling bags, are the first objects that need to be separated from the recycling stream at Waste Management’s facility on Neville Island.</p>",
    "background": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.15.jpg",
    "background_mobile": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/mobile/tzu.plastic.15.jpg"
  },
  {
    "slide_type": "image",
    "story_number": 15,
    "background": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.15.jpg",
    "background_mobile": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/mobile/tzu.plastic.15.jpg",
    "background_opacity": "0, 0, 0, 0.05"
  },
  {
    "slide_type": "image",
    "story_number": 16,
    "body": "<p style=\"text-align: left !important;\">Erika Deyarmin-Young, spokesperson for Waste Management, stands in front of a freshly dumped pile of recyclables at the tipping floor of the recycling facility at Neville Island. This is the result of single-stream recycling, where materials are mixed together and need to be separated in a labor-intensive process. </p>",
    "background": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.16.jpg",
    "background_mobile": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/mobile/tzu.plastic.16.jpg",
    "background_opacity": "0, 0, 0, 0.7"
  },
  {
    "slide_type": "image",
    "story_number": 16,
    "body": "<p style=\"text-align: left !important;\">Before the mid-1990s plastics, glass and paper were usually collected separately. This simplified the process at the recycling facilities and made it easier to resell the collected materials.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: left !important;\">Single stream became the norm as China was willing to import the resulting mix of recyclables. But China’s 2018 policy change sharply limited the ability of recycling companies to export plastics there.</p>",
    "background": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/tzu.plastic.16.jpg",
    "background_mobile": "https://ps-apps-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/recycling_june_2019/mobile/tzu.plastic.16.jpg",
    "background_opacity": "0, 0, 0, 0.7"
  },
  {
